### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

The default behavior of PseudoApplicationComponentFixture#detectChanges is to:
1. flush effects
2. run change detection
3. flush effects

Cf. https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/2b802587f27186baa493c1dd01f42d568b652f38/packages/core/testing/src/component_fixture.ts#L275-L288

The problem is that the second flush might trigger effects that affect the view (by writing to other signals) but neither `detectChanges()` nor `autoDetectChanges()` trigger change detection.

```ts
@Component({template: '{{title()}}'})
class Example {
  title = signal('');
  constructor() {
    effect(() => {
      this.title.set('demo');
    }, {allowSignalWrites: true});
  }
}

// 1. effect is flushed but change detection is not triggered a second time
const fixture = TestBed.createComponent(Example);
fixture.detectChanges(); // or autoDetectChanges()
expect(fixture.nativeElement.textContent).toEqual('demo'); // ðŸ›‘

// 2. change detection must be triggered manually after the first flush
...
fixture.detectChanges(); // or autoDetectChanges()
fixture.detectChanges();
expect(fixture.nativeElement.textContent).toEqual('demo'); // âœ…
```


### Proposed solution

Fixing this issue https://github.com/angular/angular/issues/53844 should solve this.
Thanks @atscott!

### Alternatives considered

A simple (temporary?) alternative is to make `EffectScheduler#flush()` return whether the queue was empty or not and make `autoDetectChanges()` keep triggering change detection until the queue is empty.

The problem with this approach is that it creates a different behavior that is less symmetric to app execution.

Adds the ability to specify content that Angular should fall back to if nothing is projected into an `ng-content` slot. For example, if we have the following setup

```
@Component({
  selector: 'my-comp',
  template: `
    <ng-content select="header">Default header</ng-content>
    <ng-content select="footer">Default footer</ng-content>
  `
})
class MyComp {}

@Component({
  template: `
    <my-comp>
      <footer>New footer</footer>
    </my-comp>
  `
})
class MyApp {}
```

The instance of `my-comp` in the app will have the default header and the new footer.

**Note:** Angular's content projection happens during creation time. This means that dynamically changing the contents of the slot will not cause the default content to show up, e.g. if a `if` block goes from `true` to `false`.

Fixes #12530.

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

With the `@Output` decorator, I used to check the `observed` of the `EventEmitter` (because it inherits `Subject`) to enable/disable some features.

For example, `<lu-select (clueChange)="..." />` would display a search bar in `LuSelect` component but `<lu-select />` would not.

This solution seems elegant as it avoid an additional input that would lead to unwanted cases:

- Both `<lu-select enableClue (clueChange)="..." />` and `<lu-select />` would work
- `<lu-select (clueChange)="..." />` would be useless because the search bar is not disabled because `enableClue = false`
- `<lu-select enableClue />` would be useless because the search bar is displayed, but nobody listen to its value

### Proposed solution

Add a `getter`property `observed` in [OutputEmitterRef](https://angular.dev/api/core/OutputEmitterRef)

([in this file](https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/edc1740d7e7f0296c719c7176c24031f55ae1487/packages/core/src/authoring/output/output_emitter_ref.ts#L33))

```ts
export class OutputEmitterRef<T> implements OutputRef<T> {
  private listeners: Array<(value: T) => void>|null = null;

  get observed(): boolean {
    return !!this.listeners?.length;
  }

  //...
}
```

### Alternatives considered

Replace existing usages of `emitter.observed` by inputs.

